Creative gaming¶

Game telemetry dataset used for the Creative Gaming: Propensity-to-Buy Modeling case

Feature descriptions¶

  • converted: Purchased the Zalon campain ("yes" or "no")
  • GameLevel: Highest level of game achieved by the user
  • NumGameDays: Number of days user played the game in last month (with or without network connection)
  • NumGameDays4Plus: Number of days user played the game in last month with 4 or more total users (this implies using a network connection)
  • NumInGameMessagesSent: Number of in-game messages sent to friends
  • NumFriends: Number of friends to which the user is connected (necessary to crew together in multiplayer mode)
  • NumFriendRequestIgnored: Number of friend requests this user has not replied to since game inception
  • NumSpaceHeroBadges: Number of "Space Hero" badges, the highest distinction for gameplay in Space Pirates
  • AcquiredSpaceship: Flag if the user owns a spaceship, i.e., does not have to crew on another user's or NPC's space ship ("no" or "yes")
  • AcquiredIonWeapon: Flag if the user owns the powerful "ion weapon" ("no" or "yes")
  • TimesLostSpaceship: The number of times the user destroyed his/her spaceship during gameplay. Spaceships need to be re-acquired if destroyed.
  • TimesKilled: Number of times the user was killed during gameplay
  • TimesCaptain: Number of times in last month that the user played in the role of a captain
  • TimesNavigator: Number of times in last month that the user played in the role of a navigator
  • PurchasedCoinPackSmall: Flag if the user purchased a small pack of Zathium in last month ("no" or "yes")
  • PurchasedCoinPackLarge: Flag if the user purchased a large pack of Zathium in last month ("no" or "yes")
  • NumAdsClicked: Number of in-app ads the user has clicked on
  • DaysUser: Number of days since user established a user ID with Creative Gaming (for Space Pirates or previous games)
  • UserConsole: Flag if the user plays Creative Gaming games on a console ("no" or "yes")
  • UserHasOldOS: Flag if the user has iOS version 10 or earlier ("no" or "yes")
  • training: Dummy variable that splits the dataset into a training (1) and test (0) dataset

#"converted_yes" which indicates if the gamer had purchased the Zalon campaign, rises as well.
#This implies that there is a positive relationship between the predictor variable and the outcome variable.
#the Number of "Space Hero" badges

#Regarding the second prediction plot we see that it has a slope that is under the threshold which showcases a weak relationship between the predictor/explanatory variable, 
#in this case NumFriendRequestIgnored and the dependent variable,"converted_yes" which indicates if the gamer had purchased the Zalon campaign.
#This means that the predicted probabilities of the explanatory variable do not change as much as the dependent variable increases which indicates that the explanatory variable is not strongly associated with the outcome variable.

#As for the latter three prediction plots again we see that all the curves are under the threshold which means that 
#it suggests that the relationship between the number of ads clicked and the probability of the outcome variable (represented on the y-axis) 
#is weak or non-existent. In other words, the number of ads clicked may not be a strong predictor of the outcome variable.
# it suggests that the relationship between Game Level and the probability of the outcome variable (represented on the y-axis) is weak or non-existent. In other words, the Game Level variable may not be a strong predictor of the outcome variable.
#The slope of the prediction plot represents the change in the predicted probability of the outcome variable as the predictor variable (Game Level) increases. 
#If the slope is under the threshold, it indicates that the predicted probabilities of the outcome variable are not changing much as the Game Level variable increases,
#and therefore the Game Level variable may not be strongly associated with the outcome variable.

#Profit: To calculate the profit, you need to know the total revenue from selling Zalon 
#to customers in group 1 and subtract the cost of not serving ads to these customers.
#The cost of not serving ads to a customer for 2 weeks is $1.50 in lost coin purchases, 
#and the revenue from selling Zalon is $14.99. You can calculate the profit by multiplying 
#the number of customers who purchased Zalon by the revenue from selling Zalon and
#subtracting the cost of not serving ads to all customers in group 1.

#Response rate: To calculate the response rate, you need to know the number of customers
#who purchased Zalon in the 2 months after the experiment.
#You can divide this number by the total number of customers in group 1 (30,000). 
#This will give you the response rate for group 1.

## Part III
#Response rate: To calculate the response rate, you need to know the number of customers
#who purchased Zalon in the 2 months after the experiment.
#You can divide this number by the total number of customers in group 1 (30,000). 
#This will give you the response rate for group 1.

# Group 1

group1_data = pd.read_pickle("data/cg_organic_control.pkl") # includes 30000 customers

group1_data["converted_yes"] = rsm.ifelse(group1_data.converted == "yes", 1, 0)

# Calculate response rate and profit of group 1
converted_group1 = group1_data[group1_data["converted_yes"] == 1].shape[0]
total_group1 = group1_data.shape[0]

response_rate_group1 = converted_group1 / total_group1

# The cost of serving ads to a consumer for 2 weeks is $1.50 in lost coin purchases.
# But in group one we do not serve ads so we do not include it in profit calculation
profit_group1 = converted_group1 * 14.99 
print("Response rate for Group 1:", response_rate_group1)
print("Profit for Group 1:", profit_group1)

Response rate for Group 1: 0.05686666666666667
Profit for Group 1: 25572.94

# Group 3

# Use the logistic regression model to predict the probability of purchasing the Zalon campaign

lr = smf.glm(
    formula="converted_yes ~ GameLevel + NumGameDays + NumGameDays4Plus + NumInGameMessagesSent + NumSpaceHeroBadges + NumFriendRequestIgnored + NumFriends + AcquiredSpaceship + AcquiredIonWeapon + TimesCaptain + TimesNavigator + PurchasedCoinPackSmall + PurchasedCoinPackLarge + NumAdsClicked + DaysUser + UserConsole + UserHasOldOS",
    family=Binomial(link=logit()),
    data=cg_organic.query("training == 1")
).fit()


group23_data["score"] = lr.predict(group23_data)

# Select the 30,000 customers with best predictions (scores) that are not part of group 2
group3_data = group23_data[group23_data["rnd_30k"] != 1] # 120000 customers after taking out group 2
group3_data_best = group3_data.sort_values(by="score", ascending=False).head(30000)  # top 30000

# Calculate the conversion rate of group 3
response_rate_group3 = group3_data_best["converted_yes"].astype(float).mean()

# Calculate the profit of group 3
profit_group3 = response_rate_group3 * 14.99 * 30000 - (1.5 * 30000)

# Print the result
print("The response rate of group 3 is {:.2f}%".format(response_rate_group3 * 100))
print("The profit of group 3 is ${:,.2f}".format(profit_group3))

The response rate of group 3 is 21.50%
The profit of group 3 is $51,670.51

# 4: Answer Mi Haruki’s question: “Please report back to me how well the ads are working in 
# terms of conversion rates and profits and by how much the model improves these metrics,
# all based on targeting 30,000 customers.”

# Answer: Based on the given information, we can make the following observations:

# The response rate and profit for Group 2 (30,000 customers who were served in-app ads) are lower than those for Group 3 (30,000 customers who were selected by the model to receive in-app ads).
# Both Group 2 and Group 3 have higher response rates and profits than Group 1 (30,000 customers who were not served in-app ads).
# The model-selected Group 3 has the highest response rate and profit among the three groups.
# Overall, these results suggest that the in-app ads are effective in increasing Zalon conversions. 
# The model-selected group, which received in-app ads based on the predictive model, 
# had the highest response rate and profit, indicating that the model is effective in identifying
# customers who are likely to convert with the in-app ad. The profit improvement for Group 3 
# compared to Group 1 was around $26,000, indicating a significant benefit from using the predictive model to
# target customers with in-app ads.

print('AUC for organic model:', auc_org)
print('AUC for 120k model:', auc120)

# Why are they different?
# What do you find?


# From the plot and the AUC scores, we can see that the ad model does not outperforms the organic model. 
# Also The AUC for the ad model (0.6421) is less than the AUC for the organic model (0.80966).
# But this is unexpected and is the result of Overfitting. This means that the model performs well on
# the training data but poorly on new, unseen data. This can happen when a model is too complex for the 
# amount of data available, or when the model is too closely tuned to the training data and does not 
# generalize well to new data. Overfitting can also occur when a model is trained for too many iterations, 
# or when too many features are used in the model, causing it to fit the noise in the data instead 
# of the underlying patterns.

# 6
# What could be the value of collecting data for group 1 (cg_organic_control)
# given that we already had data on organic conversions from the cg_organic data?

# Answer:
# Collecting data for group 1 (cg_organic_control) could provide a comparison group to help determine
# the true effect of the in-app ads. By having a control group, we can compare the outcomes 
# (such as conversion rates and profits) of those who were exposed to the ad (in the treatment group) 
# to those who were not (in the control group). This can help us determine whether the observed differences 
# in outcomes are truly due to the ad, or whether they could have occurred by chance. 
# In other words, the control group can help us isolate the effect of the ad and determine 
# its true impact on conversions and profits.

auc_org1 = rsm.auc(cg_organic['converted_yes'], cg_organic['pred_logit'], 1)
auc_ad = rsm.auc(group3_data2['converted_yes'], group3_data2['pred_logit_ad'], 1)

print('AUC for organic model:', auc_org1)
print('AUC for ad model:', auc_ad)

# What do you find?

# From the plot and the AUC scores, we can see that the ad model does not outperforms the organic model. 
# Also the AUC for the ad model (0.70280) is less than the AUC for the organic model (0.80966).
# But this is unexpected and is the result of Overfitting. This means that the model performs well on
# the training data but poorly on new, unseen data. This can happen when a model is too complex for the 
# amount of data available, or when the model is too closely tuned to the training data and does not 
# generalize well to new data. Overfitting can also occur when a model is trained for too many iterations, 
# or when too many features are used in the model, causing it to fit the noise in the data instead 
# of the underlying patterns.

## Now we are train a random forest on the sample of customers who were exposed to the ad campaign.
# importing the required libraries
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, precision_score, recall_score, f1_score
## preparing the data
X = group23_data.drop(['converted', 'converted_yes'], axis=1) # drop the 'converted' column and target variable
y = group23_data['converted_yes'] # set the 'converted_yes' column as the target variable

# split the data
X_train = X[X['rnd_30k'] == 1]
y_train = y[X['rnd_30k'] == 1]

X_test = X[X['rnd_30k'] == 0]
y_test = y[X['rnd_30k'] == 0]

# encode the categorical variables
X_train = pd.get_dummies(X_train)
X_test = pd.get_dummies(X_test)

# train the model
rf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, max_depth=5, class_weight='balanced', random_state=42)
rf.fit(X_train, y_train)
